This is an R Markdown document containing R analyses for the following work:

Bundy RA, Hogle SL, Barbeau KA. Fe-binding ligand production and microbial community composition in microcosm incubations. In prep

The analyses were doing here are going to be using the R package phyloseq. There are some great tutorials on how to use phyloseq here. In addition, the data that were using here has been generated by an OTU pipeline based mainly on UPARSE. There is a lot of great information at the UPARSE website. I will also write a blog post describing our pipeline in detail sometime in the near future

Load required libraries

library("phyloseq")
library("ggplot2")
library("ape")
library("vegan")
library("MASS")
library("DESeq2")
library("grid")

Check package versions

packageVersion("phyloseq")
packageVersion("ggplot2")
packageVersion("DESeq2")

Import the dataset

# Create OTU matrix
otumat <- as.matrix(read.table("allsamples_otu_table", row.names=1, sep="\t", header=TRUE))
# Create a taxonomy matrix
taxmat <- as.matrix(read.table("tax_table", row.names=1, sep="\t", header=TRUE))
# Create metadata data frame
metamat <- as.data.frame(read.table("allsamples.metadata", row.names=1, sep="\t", header=TRUE))
# Read in a phylogenetic tree for the OTUs
tree <- read.tree("bacteria_final_phylo.tre")

Generate phyloseq object

Here well call some of phyloseqs functions to genearate an object called cce12 that contains metadata, OTU, and taxonomy info.

OTU = otu_table(otumat, taxa_are_rows = TRUE)
TAX = tax_table(taxmat)
SAMPDAT = sample_data(metamat)
cce12 = phyloseq(OTU, TAX, SAMPDAT, tree)

Preprocessing data

Well remove OTUs that do not appear more than 3 times in at least 15% of samples

cce12gf = genefilter_sample(cce12, filterfun_sample(function(x) x > 3), A = 0.15 * nsamples(cce12))
cce12gfpt = prune_taxa(cce12gf, cce12)

Now well standardize abundances to the median sequencing depth of each sample

total = median(sample_sums(cce12gfpt))
cce12norm = transform_sample_counts(cce12gfpt, function(x) total * x/sum(x))

Richness/alpha diversity of data partitioned by Fe_Treatment

Here well make some richness plots of our data separated by high iron and low iron treatments. We use raw data instead of the normalized data here because many richness estimates are based on singletons and doubletons. We need to leave them in order to get meaningful estimates.

p = plot_richness(cce12, x = "Fe_Treatment", color = "Sample_ID")
p + geom_point(data = p$data, aes(x = Fe_Treatment, y = value, color = Sample_ID), size = 4)

Right now, we actually only care about richness plots of Chao1 and Shannon diversity so well just select those

psub = plot_richness(cce12, x = "Fe_Treatment", color = "Sample_ID", measures = c("Shannon", "Simpson"))
psub + geom_point(data = psub$data, aes(x = Fe_Treatment, y = value, color = Sample_ID), size = 4)

Bar plots

Now lets make some bar plots to get a fuller picture as to how the top OTUs are distributed throughout our Fe treatments. Here well select just OTUs falling into the domain Bacteria and then only take the top 20 most abundant from the normalized dataset cce12norm

cce12normbac = subset_taxa(cce12norm, Domain == "Bacteria")
TopNOTUs = names(sort(taxa_sums(cce12normbac), TRUE)[1:20])
cce12norm20 = prune_taxa(TopNOTUs, cce12normbac)
plot_bar(cce12norm20, "Sample_ID", fill = "OTU", facet_grid = ~Genus)

Detecting differential abundance of particular OTUs between Fe Treatments

Paul McMurdie says not to rarify your microbiome data. A better alternative is to model microbiome counts with a Negative Binomial model as implemented in the very popular package DESeq2 for detecting differential expression in RNAseq data. Here we use DESeq2 to test whether any particular OTUs are significantly less or more abundant in high iron versus low iron treatments.

Import data with phyloseq, convert to DESeq2s DESeqDataSet class

FeTreat.dds = phyloseq_to_deseq2(cce12, ~ Fe_Treatment)

Calculate geometric means prior to estimate size factors

gm_mean = function(x, na.rm=TRUE){
  exp(sum(log(x[x > 0]), na.rm=na.rm) / length(x))
}
geoMeans = apply(counts(FeTreat.dds), 1, gm_mean)
FeTreat.dds = estimateSizeFactors(FeTreat.dds, geoMeans = geoMeans)

Running DESeq2 on non transformed data

FeTreat.dds = DESeq(FeTreat.dds, fitType="local")
res = results(FeTreat.dds)
res = res[order(res$padj, na.last=NA), ]
alpha = 0.05
sigtab = res[(res$padj < alpha), ]
sigtab = cbind(as(sigtab, "data.frame"), as(tax_table(cce12)[rownames(sigtab), ], "matrix"))
write.table(sigtab, file = "diff_abun_OTU.tsv", sep = "\t", row.names = T)
sigtab_red = subset(sigtab, select = -c(Domain, Phylum, Order, Family))
knitr::kable(sigtab_red)

So it appears that there are 7 OTUs that are significantly more abundant in high Fe treatments (those with a negative log2 Fold-change) and three that are less abundant (genus: Eionea, Pelagibacter, and Marinimicrobia).

Plot annotated trees using subsets of the taxonomy

Another cool thing you can do is plot the phylogenetic tree of your OTUs with data overlaid

gpac <- subset_taxa(cce12, Class == "Gammaproteobacteria")
plot_tree(gpac, color = "Fe_Treatment", size = "abundance", min.abundance = 200, label.tips = "taxa_names")

Ordination of data using phyloseq, vegan, ggplot and some other stuff

Finally well make an ordination based on our community data and fit continuous environmental variable to it as factors

First define a function veganotu for extracting an OTU table from a phyloseq object and coercing it into a form vegan likes

veganotu <- function(physeq) {
    OTU <- otu_table(physeq)
    if (taxa_are_rows(OTU)) {
        OTU <- t(OTU)
    }
    return(as(OTU, "matrix"))
}

Convert physeq metadata into vanilla R data frames

keepvariables = which(sapply(sample_data(cce12), is.numeric))
physeqsd = data.frame(sample_data(cce12))[keepvariables]
physeqsd = subset(physeqsd, select = -Fe_level)
treatment = data.frame(sample_data(cce12))["Fe_Treatment"]

Using the normalized OTU matrix in the metaMDS function

vegOTU <- vegdist(veganotu(cce12norm)) #creates a bray-curtis dissimilarity matrix
set.seed(4019)
vare.mds <- isoMDS(vegOTU)

Use the score function to load sample sites into vectors. We also use plot_ordination function with the justDF option =TRUE in order to load the specific coordinates of just the OTUs.

scrs.site <- as.data.frame(scores(vare.mds, display = "sites"))
scrs.site <- cbind(scrs.site, treatment = treatment)
scrs.spp <- plot_ordination(cce12norm, vare.mds, type = "species", justDF = T) # To get species coordinates

Now we use the envfit function to fit vectors to our continuous environmental data

set.seed(152)
ef <- envfit(vare.mds, physeqsd, permu = 999)

Use the score function again, but this time to load direction of environmental vectors. Environmental vectors here are weighted by R2 value

scrs.vct <- as.data.frame(scores(ef, display = "vectors"))
vct.pvals <- ef[['vectors']]['pvals'] # ef is a list of lists. to get pvals you need the pvals list from the vectors list
scrs.vct <- cbind(scrs.vct, vct.pvals) # combine the two
scrs.vct <- scrs.vct[scrs.vct$pvals < 0.1,  ]  # select only rows with a P value < 0.1

And finally, create the plot using ggplot

ggplot(scrs.site) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = Dim1, y = Dim2, shape = Fe_Treatment), size = 6) + 
  coord_fixed() + ## need aspect ratio of 1!
  geom_segment(data = scrs.vct, aes(x = 0, xend = Dim1/5, y = 0, yend = Dim2/5), arrow = arrow(length = unit(0.25, "cm")), colour = "black") +
  geom_text(data = scrs.vct, aes(x = Dim1/4.8, y = Dim2/4.8, label = rownames(scrs.vct)), size = 3) +
  geom_point(data = scrs.spp, mapping = aes(x = Dim1, y = Dim2, color = Phylum))
